<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18420228-1112">
               <interp inst="t18420228-1112" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18420228"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18420228-1112" type="date" value="18420228"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18420228-1112-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1112-18420228 t18420228-1112-offence-1 t18420228-1112-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1112. <persName id="def1-1112-18420228" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1112-18420228" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1112-18420228" type="surname" value="STANHOPE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1112-18420228" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">HENRY STANHOPE</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420228-1112-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420228-1112-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420228-1112-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18420228-cd-237" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420228-1112-offence-1 t18420228-cd-237"></join>14th of October</rs>, 1 ring, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18420228-name-1437" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1437" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1437" type="surname" value="GOWLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1437" type="given" value="WILLIAM EDWARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1437" type="occupation" value="Excise Officer"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420228-1112-offence-1 t18420228-name-1437"></join>William Edward Gowland</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. PHILLIPS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420228-name-1438" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1438" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1438" type="surname" value="GOWLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1438" type="given" value="ELIZABETH HARRIET"></interp>ELIZABETH HARRIETT GOWLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of William Edward Gowland of Hertford-road, Vauxhall—he is in the Excise Office—I am acquainted with the family of the French's, who live in Bond-street, Vaux<lb></lb>hall—I took tea and spent the evening there on the 13th of October in</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184202280227"></xptr>
               <p>the front parlour—I had my rings on when I went there—I had occasion in the course of that afternoon, while there, to take my rings off, for the purpose of washing my hands up stairs—among others, I took off a pearl hoop ring—I returned into the parlour and put on what I supposed to be all the rings I had taken off—when I returned home that night I did not miss anything, but the next day I missed this pearl hoop ring, now pro<lb></lb>duced—I sent to Mr. French's to inquire about it—I am in the habit of constantly wearing this ring—it is worth about 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—it was the guard ring given me on my marriage.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You cannot positively swear where you lost it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I know I had it that day, and I know I lost it that day—I missed it the next morning—I had it on, the day I was at Mrs. French's, and I was no where else—t always wear it—I know I had it in the evening—I never took it off after I put it on—I took off my rings at Mrs. French's, but I do not remember taking off this particular ring.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was this the outside ring? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You put on the rings that you took off to the best of your belief? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—after sitting there I walked home that night—I live about five minutes' walk from Mrs. French's—Mrs. and Miss French have known me about four years—Miss French taught my children—she knew me perfectly well, and I suppose she knew my ring—I do not know whether Mrs. French knew my ring—I seldom saw her—Miss French came to my house as governess—I visited Mrs. French perhaps two or three times—I had seen her frequently—she had been at my house, I cannot tell how many times—perhaps ten times—she had an opportunity of seeing my ring, but a guard ring is so usual to wear, that I should not suppose she noticed it—it is a common ring.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is there nothing remarkable about it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, it has been taken in—I had never seen the prisoner—he had never seen my ring—he was not there the night I lost it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you at all conscious of having dropped the ring from your finger? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I could not, it fitted so very tight—I had not tan to any body's house between the evening when I took it off at Mrs. French's and missing it the following morning—I know I put it on the morning that I went to Mrs. French's—I had not taken my rings off for the purpose of washing my fingers, or any other purpose of that sort before I went to Mrs. French's, but I took them off there—my infant was there, and I fancied she had knocked it down—there was no other place at which I could have dropped it—I took all my rings off in Mrs. French's parlour, with the exception of one diamond ring, and I put all on, as I supposed, that I took off.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420228-name-1439" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1439" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1439" type="surname" value="FRENCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1439" type="given" value="ELIZA SARAH"></interp>ELIZA SARAH FRENCH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am single, and live with my parents, in Bond-street, Vauxhall. I know the prisoner, and I know Mrs. Gowland—I remember, on the 13th of October, she drank tea at my mother's, in the front parlour—on the morning of the 14th I remember seeing the prisoner—I should think about ten o'clock—the parlour bad not been cleaned up at that time—I went into the parlour on being informed the prisoner was there—I found him there—my mother came into the room, and went out, and came back again—the prisoner on that occasion pro<lb></lb>duced this ring to me—(<hi rend="italic">looking at it</hi>)—he asked me to try it on, and asked if it fitted me—I tried it on, and soon after my mamma entered the said to her, "See what a pretty ring Mr. Stanhope has given me"—after I left the room.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184202280228"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> In what capacity was Mr. Stanhope received at your house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He was paying his addresses to me—he represented himself to be a gen<lb></lb>tleman of 300<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a-year, with 9000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in the funds—I saw him again on Sunday, the 17th of October, at our house, and afterwards we went to take tea at his house in Newton-terrace—when I was at his apartment I perceived him drawing the ring off my finger—I said to him, "what are you doing?"—he said, "Oh, I wish to get you another ring made, a diamond and ruby ring"—he said, "Don't be afraid, you shall have this again; I only wish to take it to the jeweller's to get you a better; you shall have this returned with the diamond and ruby ring"—I allowed him to take it on that representation—I never saw this ring again till the day he was at Union-hall—it was produced there—he never gave me the dia<lb></lb>mond and ruby ring, nor this one back.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You are a governess, are you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I was governess to Mrs. Gowland's children, and I have had other pupils—I am twenty-one years of age—I am sorry to say I met with the prisoner, and formed an acquaintance with him in an omnibus—I did not ask him to my house, upon my oath—I have no one who pays his addresses to me now—I know a Mr. Logan, as a friend—I knew him before I knew the prisoner—I, and my mamma, and my sister were out—there was a crowd, Mr. Logan very kindly offered to take us through the crowd, and this we became acquainted with him—he made no pretensions, but he called at our house occasionally.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> The prisoner called on you on the Sunday, and you went to his house, did you not go rather before your mamma? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, my mamma and papa were not quite ready, and the prisoner said we would walk on first—my papa came to the house afterwards, but he was not there when I went—I went with the prisoner, and went into the parlour—I swear I was never in his bed-room—I did not take tea in his bed-room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did not you and mamma take tea in the prisoner's bed-room, and has he any other room in the house but that bed-room? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, he had—people do not generally take tea in the bed-room—my mamma had not come to the house when the prisoner took the ring off—upon my oath the ring was taken off in the parlour—I am quite sure of that—no one was present but the prisoner and me—the people of the house were Dot pre<lb></lb>sent—that parlour is a room of which the prisoner has the exclusive use—he and I were there perhaps half-an-hour before mamma came—I did not consider there was any impropriety in being alone with him, when I was to be united to him at Christmas—he got the ring away on that oc<lb></lb>casion—I am sure he has never given me the ruby ring since—I have never had it to this day, nor any other ring from him—he brought one to try on, but took it away again.</p>
               <p>MR. PHILLIPS. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were your father and mother aware that be was paying his addresses to you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—he made the same represents<lb></lb>tions to them that he did to me—that he was the eldest son, and heir to an estate—I received his addresses with their full approbation and con<lb></lb>sent, believing his representation, and that every thing was right and proper—when I met with him in the omnibus, I had a parcel containing some books—I had been to take a German lesson—he entered into con<lb></lb>versation with me in the omnibus, and was telling me about foreign countries, and of his father's cruelty in wishing him to marry a young lady to whom he was not attached—when we got out, he said, "I hope</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184202280229"></xptr>
               <p>you will allow me to see you home"—I said, "Oh dear no, a servant will meet me," but I was a few minutes earlier than usual, and the servant had not come—the prisoner wished to go with me—I said I did not con<lb></lb>sider it was proper, I was obliged to him—I left him, and when I had gone two or three steps, I found he was running after me—he said he hoped I inspected him of nothing, that it was a gentlemanly act, and he did it out of pure kindness—I said I did not suspect him of any thing but kindness, and he went on till I met the servant—he still continued with me—I let him do so, as I thought he would think I suspected him of improper motives—he went with me to the house, but he did not go in, but before this he pretended he had fallen in love with me, and pretended to the purest morality and religion, and great kindness of character.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420228-name-1440" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1440" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1440" type="surname" value="SHOWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1440" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES SHOWELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of Mr. Spink, of Gracechnrch-street, a pawnbroker. I took in this pearl ring on the 18th of October, 1841, and advanced 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on it—this is the duplicate I gave with it—to the best of my belief the prisoner is the man who pawned it—I could not swear positively to him, from the lapse of time, and not having seen the person before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420228-name-1441" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1441" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1441" type="surname" value="WOODLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1441" type="given" value="ALICE"></interp>ALICE WOODLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my aunt, at No. 9, Newton-terrace, Ken<lb></lb>mington-green. The prisoner took two rooms in my aunt's house in Oc<lb></lb>tober last—he left about the 3rd of December—he gave a notice of his intention to leave, but he went off without our knowing it—in conse<lb></lb>quence of some suspicion, I examined a pocket-book that was in his bed<lb></lb>room, I think about a fortnight before he left, I cannot be sure—I took a copy of some duplicates that were in it—this is a copy of one of them—(<hi rend="italic">reads</hi>)—"D. E. Spink, 2, Gracechurch-street, 18th of October, 1841; I ring, 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. Williams, Kennington-green."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was his property left in your house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; he took it with him—I do not know whose house he went to when he left us—I did not know that he went to Mrs. French's—he went to Mrs. French's for fourteen or fifteen days while he was living with us, and it was after he came back from there, that he left our house—he owed us 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for rent when he left, and for some paint—his rent was 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-week—fifteen days of the last month he was at Mrs. French's—the former month's rent was paid—he took it by the month, but to pay Weekly—he came in on the 6th of October—he did not pay up to the 9th of November—there were about 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. left, I think—at the end of the first month her removed into another room—I was once charged falsely with pawning other people's property, but I did not do it—the Magistrate convicted me—I do not know of any particular visit paid by Miss French to the prisoner—she was there very often—she used to come sometimes with the family—I do not know whether she was oftener there without her mother than with her—she has been there without her mother.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420228-name-1442" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1442" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1442" type="surname" value="LANGLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1442" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES LANGLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am uncle-in-law to Alice Woodley. I remem<lb></lb>ber the day on which she examined the duplicates, I examined them—this is the paper which contains a copy of them—she wrote it by my direc<lb></lb>tion—I saw her do it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What are you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I am out of any kind of employment, and I have been very ill for two years—I have been a general accountant—at other times I was clerk to a solicitor—I am not so now—I am not hanging about the Insolvent Court—I have not been there for two years or more—I did act in the name of Mr. Patterson of Mincing-lane</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184202280230"></xptr>
               <p>—it is three or four years since I was employed by him—I have since done business for Mr. Hughes of Clifford's Inn, in the Insolvent Court, but that Court has not seen me for two years, nor any other Court except this Court to-day—Woodley's family are of the highest respectability in Cork, and so are my wife's family.</p>
               <p>MR. PHILLIPS. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you let your rooms out in lodgings? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420228-name-1443" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1443" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1443" type="surname" value="GOWLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-name-1443" type="given" value="WILLIAM EDWARD"></interp>WILLIAM EDWARD GOWLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the husband of Mrs. Gowland, who identified the ring—this is it—I have not the least doubt of the iden<lb></lb>tity of it—I gave it to Mrs. Gowland a day or two before our marriage—she has worn it for seventeen years.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Mrs. Gowland seems to have a great many rings? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> She wears three or four—this was the guard to her wedding-ring—I know this from its general character, and from its having been taken in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18420228-1112-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18420228-1112-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420228-1112-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
            </div1>
